d previously available only or primarily in Yiddish. Through personal queries about how to live Torah-instructed lives and rabbinic responses, the reader is invited to enter the world of Jewish Maramarosh, where Hasidism flourished and rabbinic scholarship reflected human nobility manifested through the pragmatics of poverty and the dynamics of living closely with nature. Professor Slomovic, recognizing the fluidity and balance over time provided by Talmudic thought as exemplified through rabbinic teaching, invites the reader to join the discourse on the everyday life of everyday people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aCohen, Aryeh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.1 aLandy, Caryn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.1 aLowenstein, Steven M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertASP eBook Package Backlist 2008-2015z978311068814640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781618112439423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781618112439.jpg  a978-3-11-068814-6  ASP eBook Package Backlist 2008-2015c2008d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG